### Describe the Issue

The formula given for converting from C to F is given as 

a) `F = C * 9.0 / 5 + 32`

But this can also be written as 

b) `F = 9.0 / 5 * C + 32`

These two formulas are producing different results. Using `26` for `C` (which is used in the tests) we get:

a) `26 * 9.0 / 5 + 32 = 78.8`

b) `9.0 / 5 * 26 + 32 = 78.80000000000001`

If formula `b` is used then the tests for this challenge will fail due to the floating point rounding issue.


### Affected Page

https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/javascript-algorithms-and-data-structures/es6/use-getters-and-setters-to-control-access-to-an-object

### Your code

```
class Thermostat  {
  constructor(f) {
    this._temp = f;
  }
  get temperature() {
    return 5.0 / 9.0 * (this._temp - 32.0);
  }
  set temperature(c) {
    this._temp = 9.0 / 5.0 * c + 32.0;
  }
}
```


### Expected behavior

The tests should pass regardless of where C is placed in the formula. Either we need to do a little rounding in the tests or replace `26` with a different number in the tests that won't produce different results depending on the placement of C in the formula.

